seal     : A proton is not solid — it is three quarks held in a roaring field of gluons, the carriers of the strong force. Quarks carry 'colour charge,' and the force between them is so strange that they can never be isolated: pull two apart and the binding field stretches like a band, storing energy until it snaps into a fresh quark-pair. This is real physics, here drawn as ink.
